  <h2>Digital Radiology at All About Pets</h2>
  <p>
    Our in-house digital radiography system produces high-resolution images within seconds of exposure. Unlike traditional film X-rays, digital images can be immediately reviewed on screen, zoomed, adjusted, and shared — accelerating diagnosis and reducing the time your pet spends under restraint.
  </p>
  <p>
    X-rays are quick, painless, and in most cases require only brief, gentle positioning — no sedation is needed for cooperative patients.
  </p>

  <h2>What X-Rays Help Diagnose</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Fractures and bone injuries</strong> — assess breaks, chips, or abnormal bone development</li>
    <li><strong>Organ evaluation</strong> — view the size, shape, and position of the heart, lungs, liver, kidneys, spleen, and bladder</li>
    <li><strong>Foreign object detection</strong> — locate swallowed objects before they become dangerous</li>
    <li><strong>Joint disease</strong> — assess arthritis, hip dysplasia, elbow dysplasia, and other musculoskeletal conditions</li>
    <li><strong>Respiratory issues</strong> — identify pneumonia, pleural effusion, or masses in the chest cavity</li>
    <li><strong>Intestinal problems</strong> — detect obstructions, gas patterns, or abnormal organ positioning</li>
    <li><strong>Pregnancy</strong> — estimate litter size late in pregnancy</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>When Radiology Is Recommended</h2>
  <p>
    We may recommend X-rays as part of a diagnostic workup when your pet shows signs of pain, lameness, respiratory changes, abdominal discomfort, vomiting, or after a trauma event. Imaging is also commonly used before and after surgery to confirm diagnosis and verify outcomes.
  </p>
  <p>
    In some cases, radiology results allow us to diagnose and begin treatment in a single visit — sparing your pet additional stress and getting them on the path to recovery sooner.
  </p>

  <h2>Safe and Comfortable</h2>
  <p>
    We use the minimum exposure necessary to produce diagnostic-quality images. Our team is trained in low-stress handling techniques to make the process as calm as possible. For pets who are in significant pain or very anxious, mild sedation may be recommended to allow safe positioning.
  </p>

  <div class="callout">
